<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Rajasthan</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Land of Kings</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Rajasthan — Rajput + Sthan, the Land of Kings — is India's most theatrical state. Larger than Germany, it covers 342,239 sq km of extraordinary geographic and cultural contrast: the blazing Thar Desert in the west (the only major hot desert in South Asia), the ancient Aravalli mountain range in the center (the world's oldest fold mountains at 2.5 billion years), and fertile plains in the east. For a thousand years, Rajasthan was the battleground and canvas of the Rajput warrior clans — the Sisodias of Mewar, the Kachhwahas of Amber-Jaipur, the Rathores of Marwar, the Chauhans of Ajmer — who built the most spectacular military architecture in human history. Their forts — Chittorgarh (the largest fort in India), Mehrangarh (the most dramatic), Kumbhalgarh (with walls 36 km long — the world's second longest wall after the Great Wall of China), Amber, Jaisalmer — rise from the desert and hilltops with an audacity that still takes the breath away. Rajasthan's hill forts are a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Jaipur — the Pink City — was India's first planned city, laid out in 1727 by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II on a precise grid according to ancient Vastu Shastra principles. Udaipur — the City of Lakes — spreads across seven lakes with palaces reflected in their waters, earning the title of the most romantic city in Asia. Jaisalmer — the Golden City — is a living medieval fort city inhabited since 1156 AD. The Thar Desert is not barren but extraordinarily alive with culture: Bhil and Bhopa tribal communities, Kalbeliya snake charmers, Manganiyar musicians, whirling Kalbelia dervishes and camel caravans that still traverse ancient trade routes. Rajasthan's Holi is the most vivid in the world; its food is the most vivid in India; its textiles — block prints, Bandhani tie-dye, mirror work — are India's most exported craft tradition. Every palace is now a hotel; every fort a living story. Come as a traveler; leave as a romantic.</p>
