const placesData=[
{emoji:"🏰",name:"Mehrangarh Fort",location:"Jodhpur",desc:"The most dramatic fort in India — a colossal sandstone citadel rising 410 feet sheer from a rocky outcrop above the Blue City. Built in 1459 by Rao Jodha, it contains seven successive gates, extraordinary jali-screen palace apartments and a museum of Rajput arms, art and palanquins of breathtaking quality. At night, lit against the Jodhpur sky, it looks like a feature of the planet itself.",fee:["Rs.100 Indians","Rs.600 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🌟",name:"Amber Fort & Jaipur Heritage",location:"Jaipur",desc:"The Amer Fort — a UNESCO World Heritage Site — rises in terraced magnificence from the Aravalli hills above Maota Lake. The Sheesh Mahal (Hall of Mirrors) reflects a single candle into a thousand stars. Within Jaipur: the Hawa Mahal (Palace of Winds, 953 windows), the Jantar Mantar (UNESCO astronomical observatory) and the City Palace together form the most complete royal urban ensemble in India.",fee:["Rs.100 Indians","Rs.500 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🏯",name:"Chittorgarh Fort",location:"Chittorgarh District",desc:"The largest fort in India — 700 acres on a plateau 590 feet above the plains. The site of three legendary Jauhars (mass self-immolation by Rajput women to avoid capture) and the source of the Rani Padmini legend. The 15th-century Vijay Stambha (Tower of Victory) and 12th-century Kirti Stambha (Tower of Fame) are among India's finest medieval towers. A UNESCO World Heritage Site of immense historical and emotional power.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.250 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🌅",name:"Jaisalmer Fort & Sam Sand Dunes",location:"Jaisalmer District",desc:"The Golden City — a medieval fort city still inhabited, its honey-colored sandstone walls rising from the Thar Desert like a vision. UNESCO World Heritage Site. Three km of ramparts enclosing havelis, temples and narrow lanes unchanged since the 12th century. Thirty km away, the Sam Sand Dunes offer camel safaris, desert camps and sunsets of violent beauty over the Thar.",fee:["Rs.70 Indians","Rs.250 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🦅",name:"Keoladeo Ghana National Park",location:"Bharatpur",desc:"UNESCO World Heritage Site — a former royal duck-hunting reserve transformed into one of the world's greatest bird sanctuaries. In winter, 400+ species including the critically endangered Siberian crane concentrate in the wetlands. Rickshaw rides through the park at dawn in winter are among India's finest wildlife experiences. The sheer density of nesting birds in the breeding season is extraordinary.",fee:["Rs.75 Indians","Rs.500 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🛕",name:"Dilwara Jain Temples",location:"Mount Abu, Sirohi",desc:"The finest marble temple carvings on earth — five Jain temples built between the 11th and 13th centuries at Mount Abu, with ceilings so intricately carved in white marble that they resemble stone lace. The Vimal Vasahi (1031 AD) and Luna Vasahi (1230 AD) temples took 14 years each to build. The level of craftsmanship is technically impossible to explain — it has never been replicated.",fee:["Free (camera charges)"]},
{emoji:"🐆",name:"Ranthambore Tiger Reserve",location:"Sawai Madhopur",desc:"The most famous tiger reserve in India — where tigers are photographed against medieval fort ruins, temple ghats and desert scrub. The ancient Ranthambore Fort (UNESCO, within the park) adds a haunting beauty to the wildlife experience. Tigers here are habituated to vehicles and frequently photographed in full daylight. The combination of history, landscape and wildlife is unique.",fee:["Zone-wise charges"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Pushkar Lake & Brahma Temple",location:"Ajmer District",desc:"One of Hinduism's most sacred lakes — 52 bathing ghats surround a natural crater lake. The only functioning Brahma temple in the world stands on its shore. During Kartik Purnima, the Pushkar Camel Fair transforms this sacred town into the most colorful gathering in Rajasthan — 50,000 camels, 200,000 people, acrobats, snake charmers and traders from across the desert.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🪜",name:"Chand Baori — Abhaneri Step Well",location:"Dausa District",desc:"The most spectacular step well in the world — 3,500 narrow steps descending 20 meters in a perfect geometric pattern of 13 stories. Built in the 9th century, Chand Baori's mathematical precision and visual grandeur are staggering — a building that must be seen to be understood. Featured in Hollywood films and global architecture publications as a masterpiece of ancient engineering.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Kumbhalgarh Fort & Wildlife Sanctuary",location:"Rajsamand District",desc:"The second-longest wall in the world — 36 km of ramparts encircling the second-most-important Mewar fort after Chittorgarh. Built by Maharana Kumbha in the 15th century on an 1,100-meter hilltop, it sheltered Maharana Pratap as a child and was considered impregnable. The surrounding Kumbhalgarh Wildlife Sanctuary protects wolves, leopards and sloth bears. UNESCO World Heritage Site.",fee:["Rs.40 Indians","Rs.600 Foreigners"]}
];

const artsData=[
{emoji:"🖼️",name:"Phad Painting",location:"Shahpura, Bhilwara",desc:"An extraordinary Rajasthani folk painting tradition — huge painted scrolls (up to 30 feet long) depicting the life stories of folk heroes Pabuji and Devnarayan. Traditionally carried by Bhopa priests who unroll the phad and sing the story through the night. GI-tagged. The intricate figures in bright primary colors on cloth represent one of India's most ancient narrative art traditions."},
{emoji:"🧵",name:"Block Printing — Sanganer, Bagru & Bagh",location:"Jaipur, Nagaur, Dhar border",desc:"Rajasthan is the global capital of hand block printing — Sanganer's white-ground floral prints and Bagru's earthy resist prints are two distinct traditions. Hand-carved wooden blocks, natural vegetable dyes and the specific mineral-rich water of each area create prints impossible to replicate industrially. GI-tagged, these textiles are Rajasthan's most internationally exported craft."},
{emoji:"💍",name:"Meenakari Enamelwork and Kundan Jewelry",location:"Jaipur",desc:"Jaipur is the jewelry capital of India — Meenakari (colored enamel inlay on gold and silver) and Kundan (polished gold foil surrounding gemstones) are the city's supreme craft traditions. The gem-cutting industry at Jaipur handles 80% of the world's colored gemstone cutting. The Jaipur jeweler's lane (Johari Bazaar) has been a global trading center for centuries."},
{emoji:"💃",name:"Kalbeliya Dance and Manganiyar Music",location:"Thar Desert Communities",desc:"Kalbeliya — the whirling dance of the snake charmer community, in black skirts, is a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage. The Manganiyar and Langa hereditary musicians of western Rajasthan play sarangi, khartal and dholak with extraordinary skill, singing for their patron communities and festivals. Their music has been performed at Carnegie Hall and the Royal Albert Hall."},
{emoji:"🎨",name:"Miniature Painting — Rajput & Mughal Schools",location:"Jaipur, Udaipur, Bundi, Kishangarh",desc:"Rajasthan has the richest tradition of miniature painting in India — five distinct schools developed across different royal courts. The Kishangarh school produced the Bani Thani — India's Mona Lisa. The Bundi school is known for its lush landscapes. Mewar and Marwar each have distinct palettes. These paintings, often smaller than a postcard, contain entire universes."},
{emoji:"🧶",name:"Bandhani Tie-Dye and Mirror Work",location:"Jodhpur, Jaipur, Barmer",desc:"Bandhani — resist tie-dye creating dots, squares and wave patterns in vivid colors — is Rajasthan's most iconic textile. Traditionally made for weddings, the finest Bandhani requires thousands of individual tie-points per meter. Mirror-work (shisha embroidery), woven with sequins and glass into fabric, creates garments that catch light like desert stars. Both are GI-tagged crafts."}
