const traditionsData=[
{emoji:"🐪",name:"Pushkar Camel Fair",location:"Pushkar, Ajmer — October/November",desc:"The world's largest camel fair — 50,000 camels, horses and cattle traded over five days at Kartik Purnima. Acrobats, snake charmers, magicians, folk musicians and traders converge from across Rajasthan and beyond. The camel races and beauty competitions are extraordinary spectacles. The fair merges with the sacred Pushkar pilgrimage — commerce and devotion at the shore of the same lake."},
{emoji:"🎪",name:"Jaipur Literature Festival",location:"Jaipur — January",desc:"The world's largest free literary festival — 500,000 visitors over five days at the Diggi Palace gardens. Every major author, thinker, poet and public intellectual from across the world attends. Founded in 2006, it has hosted Toni Morrison, Salman Rushdie, Ben Okri, Amartya Sen and hundreds more. The combination of India's most beautiful winter city with the world's greatest literary gathering is irresistible."},
{emoji:"🔥",name:"Desert Festival, Jaisalmer",location:"Jaisalmer — January/February",desc:"Three days of Rajasthani culture against the backdrop of the Sam Sand Dunes — turban-tying competitions, camel polo, fire dances, folk music and the Mr. Desert competition. The night cultural shows with traditional performers against a moonlit desert sky are magical. The festival celebrates the living desert culture of the Thar in one of the world's most spectacular natural settings."},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Teej — Monsoon Festival of Women",location:"Jaipur, Statewide — August",desc:"Rajasthan's most beloved women's festival — celebrating the monsoon arrival and the reunion of Goddess Parvati with Shiva. Women dress in green and red, swing on flower-decorated jhulas and sing Teej songs. In Jaipur, an elaborate Teej procession carries the Teej Mata idol through the old city in the most colorful procession of the year — elephants, camels, folk dancers and royal retinue."},
{emoji:"💡",name:"Diwali in Udaipur",location:"Udaipur and Jaipur",desc:"Udaipur's Diwali is perhaps the most visually spectacular in India — the City Palace and Lake Pichola are illuminated with oil lamps reflected across the water, with fireworks bursting over the lake palaces. Jaipur's Diwali transforms the entire walled city into a glowing pink maze. The combination of Rajput architecture and festival lighting creates a visual experience of extraordinary beauty."},
{emoji:"🎊",name:"Gangaur",location:"Statewide — March/April",desc:"The most important festival for Rajasthani women — 18 days of celebrating the marital bliss of Goddess Gauri (Parvati) and Shiva. Married women pray for their husbands' longevity; unmarried women pray for good husbands. The Gangaur procession in Jaipur — women in traditional dress carrying clay idols of Gauri — is one of Rajasthan's most photogenic cultural events."}
