const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🍖",name:"Dal Baati Churma",region:"Rajasthan — National Identity Dish",desc:"The triumvirate of Rajasthani cuisine — hard wheat dough balls (baati) baked in a cow-dung fire or tandoor until perfectly charred, broken open and drowned in ghee, served with thick dal and churma (crushed baati with ghee and sugar). A dish designed for desert warriors who could bake baati in the embers while on campaign. Rich, robust, impossible to eat without contentment."},
{emoji:"🌶️",name:"Laal Maas",location:"Jodhpur and Marwar",desc:"Rajasthan's most celebrated non-vegetarian dish — tender goat cooked in a fierce sauce of Mathania red chilies (which give color and flavor without excessive heat), yogurt and whole spices. Originally a royal hunting dish, Laal Maas is cooked slowly until the meat is falling-off-the-bone and the oil surfaces brilliant red. The Mathania chili from Jodhpur is the soul of this dish."},
{emoji:"🥛",name:"Ker Sangri — Desert Vegetable",region:"Marwar and Thar",desc:"The quintessential desert vegetable preparation — ker (wild desert berries) and sangri (dried desert beans from the khejri tree) cooked with dried red chilies, cumin and mango powder. A dish that embodies the desert's philosophy: nothing wasted, everything preserved, flavor coaxed from the most austere ingredients. Ker Sangri has been eaten by Rajput warriors and desert travelers for centuries."},
{emoji:"🍬",name:"Ghewar and Rajasthani Sweets",region:"Jaipur, Statewide",desc:"Ghewar — a disc-shaped sweet made from maida batter fried in ghee in a specific cylindrical mold, soaked in sugar syrup and topped with rabri and pistachios — is Rajasthan's most iconic sweet, made especially for Teej and Gangaur festivals. Mawa Kachori of Jodhpur (a sweet fried pastry filled with mawa and dry fruits), Balushahi and Imarti round out a sweet tradition of extraordinary richness."},
{emoji:"🫓",name:"Pyaaz Kachori & Mirchi Vada",region:"Jodhpur Street Food Icons",desc:"Jodhpur's contribution to India's street food vocabulary — Pyaaz Kachori (flaky pastry stuffed with spiced onion filling, served hot with tamarind chutney) and Mirchi Vada (large green chili stuffed with spiced potato, battered and deep-fried). Both are eaten from dawn at Jodhpur's famous Sardar Market stalls. The flavors are bold, generous and entirely Rajasthani."},
{emoji:"🥘",name:"Gatte Ki Sabzi and Kadhi",region:"Statewide",desc:"Gatte — chickpea flour cylinders boiled with spices, then simmered in a yogurt-based curry — is one of Rajasthan's most beloved dishes. In a desert region where fresh vegetables are scarce, the art of cooking with dried legumes, preserved dairy and spices reached its highest expression. Rajasthani kadhi — thicker, more richly spiced than other versions — is the essential accompaniment."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Bajre Ki Roti and Lasun Chutney",region:"Rural Rajasthan",desc:"The everyday sustenance of rural Rajasthan — thick pearl millet flatbread (bajra roti) cooked on a dry tawa and eaten with raw garlic-red chili chutney, butter and jaggery. Bajra is Rajasthan's native grain — drought-resistant, nutritious and deeply flavored. The combination of bajra roti with garlic chutney and churned buttermilk (chaach) is the taste of the desert itself."},
{emoji:"🍲",name:"Rajasthani Thali — The Complete Meal",region:"Statewide",desc:"A Rajasthani thali is one of the world's great meals — an ever-replenishing spread of dal, baati, gatte ki sabzi, ker sangri, bajra roti, churma, rabri, papad, pickles, buttermilk and seasonal preparations served on a large silver or brass plate. Eating from a proper Rajasthani thali is a cultural experience: it is never finished and never the same twice."},
{emoji:"☕",name:"Kesar Chai and Rajasthani Chai Culture",region:"Jaisalmer and Jodhpur",desc:"The chai culture of Rajasthan — saffron-infused milk tea served in small glasses at desert dhabas — is one of India's most distinctive. Jaisalmer's masala chai prepared on camel safaris, or the rose sharbat and thandai of Jodhpur festivals, reflect a sophisticated beverage tradition born from the need to extract pleasure from minimal ingredients in extreme conditions."},
